# Terminal autonomy & safety

## Auto-run (no confirmation needed)

Run these **directly** when they support the current task—do not ask permission first:

- **Build / compile:** `cmake`, `ninja`, `make`, `clang`, `cargo build`, etc.
- **Test:** `ctest`, `lit`, `bash test/run_tests.sh`, project test binaries
- **Git (read + normal write):** `status`, `diff`, `log`, `branch`, `add`, `commit` (only when user asked to commit), `fetch`, `pull`, `push` (only when user asked to push)
- **Install / deps:** `pip install`, `npm install`, `apt`/`dnf` package installs when required for the task
- **Run / query:** running built binaries, `--help`, read-only `grep`/`find`/`ls`/`cat`, environment checks

Use `rtk` for noisy commands per project `.cursorrules`.

## Never auto-run — stop and ask the user

Do **not** execute; explain risk and wait for explicit approval:

- `rm -rf` or recursive delete of broad paths (`rm -r ~`, `rm -rf /`, project root wipe)
- Bulk delete: `find … -delete`, `git clean -fdx`, mass `unlink`, emptying trash on large trees
- Disk / filesystem destruction: `mkfs`, `fdisk`, `parted`, `dd` to block devices, `wipefs`, `shred` on system disks
- `git reset --hard`, `git push --force` to `main`/`master`, `git checkout .` that discards large uncommitted work—unless user explicitly requested
- `chmod -R 777`, `chown -R` on system paths, `sudo` on destructive commands
- Overwriting critical config without user intent (e.g. `> /etc/…`)

For borderline cases (deleting a few known temp files inside the repo), prefer safe targeted deletes and state what will be removed; still avoid `rm -rf` on parent directories.

## MCP tools (subagents)

All Task / audit / implementer subagents may use **any enabled MCP tool** (including code-review-graph, memorix, etc.) without asking the user for permission first. Prefer graph tools for exploration per `AGENTS.md`.

## On block

1. Quote the exact command you would have run.
2. State why it is high-risk.
3. Offer a safer alternative if one exists.
4. Proceed only after the user confirms.
